Digital Reference

Digital Reference (DR) – upper ontology introduced by the H2020/ECSEL project Productive4.0 in 2017, is a supply chain-related Semantic Web mirror of the semiconductor industry and supply chains containing semiconductors.

The Digital Reference, organized in topic clusters (lobes), provides the structure of a knowledge base readable for humans and computers alike. It represents all stages of the semiconductor supply chain with several sub-ontologies that currently consist of concepts, hierarchies and organizations (Ehm et al. 2019), (Ehm et al. 2020), (Ramzy et al. 2022).

Introduction

The concept of Digital Reference originates from the Productive4.0 initiative, aligned with the principles of Industry 4.0. Productive4.0 aimed to create a comprehensive user platform fostering digital networking across industries and value chains, inspired by the Semantic Web, Semantic Web Stack, and ontology.

At its core, this innovative approach is a Semantic Web model capturing intricate supply chain networks in the semiconductor industry and related domains. Merging distinct supply chain structures and semiconductor production concepts, it provides a holistic understanding of this complex landscape. This model includes around 800 distinct classes, representing various concepts across diverse domains. These are organized into thematic clusters known as "lobes," analogous to functional regions in the human brain. Each lobe corresponds to a specific supply chain facet, acting as a repository of knowledge accessible to both humans and machines. For instance, the "Cloud" lobe symbolizes networked remote servers for data management, the "Power" lobe covers electrical energy consumption, and the "Product" lobe encapsulates customer-tailored items and services. Additionally, lobes encompass domains like "Semiconductor Development," "Semiconductor Production," "Sensor," "Supply Chain," and "Sustainability," among others. The lobe structure facilitates the understanding and representation of supply chain elements. These lobes serve as taxonomies for classes and property clusters, bridging connections with other project components like the Arrowhead Cloud and enabling the realization of use cases.

Furthermore, when considering its practical implementation, we can turn our attention to the Applications in the SC4EU Project. Within the semiconductor domain, the SC4EU project harnesses the potential of Digital Reference. By addressing the bullwhip effect through data-driven strategies, SC4EU aims to alleviate industry challenges. Employing anonymous surveys and Multi-Party Computation technology, it effectively gathers reliable demand data. This information is then mapped onto semantic representations within the model and further processed with AI tools to achieve detailed demand breakdowns. Collaborating with advanced technologies like AI and the Semantic Web, the Digital Reference becomes a catalyst for transforming the SC4EU project. This transformation elevates the platform, enhancing demand forecasting accuracy and reducing chip shortages. Beyond immediate gains, this collaboration aligns with broader objectives, such as strengthening European digital sovereignty. The integration of cybersecurity, quality assurance, and reliability principles harmonizes with Industry 4.0 goals and the ongoing journey of digital transformation.

Lobes

Cloud

Cloud refers to a network of remote servers that store, manage, and process data and applications, providing on-demand access and scalable computing resources over the internet.

Organization

Organization refers to the structural and managerial aspects such as organizational structure, roles and responsibilities, efficient coordination and collaboration among various stakeholders within the semiconductor supply chains.

Planning

Planning is about making strategic decisions and creating comprehensive plans to ensure the efficient and effective flow of materials, products, and information throughout the manufacturing and distribution process. In includes information about marketing and sales demans, demand march, aggregated capacity, capacity bottlenecks, orders and customers.

Power

Power refers to the electrical energy consumed or dissipated by electronic devices or components during their operation, and is a crucial consideration for efficiency and performance optimization.

Process

Process refers to a series of interconnected and sequential actions, steps, or operations designed to achieve a specific outcome or goal within a system or organization.

Product

A product is a tangible or intangible item or service that is created, manufactured, or offered to fulfill a need or desire of customers.

Semiconductor Development

Semiconductor development refers to the process of researching, designing, and creating semiconductor devices to meet technological avancements and inductry demands.

Semiconductor Production

Semiconductor production refers to the manufacturing process of creating integrated circuits and other semiconductor devices by deposing, patterning, and doping various materials on a substrate to form electronic components.

Sensor

A sensor is a device or component that detects and measures physical, chemical or environmental parameters and converts them into electrical signals for futher analysis or use.

Supply Chain

Supply chain refers to a network of interconnected organizations, activities, resources, and technologies involved in the production, distribution, and delivery of goods or services from the source to end consumer.

Sustainability

Sustainability refers to the practice of meeting present needs without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs, balancing environmental, social, and economic considerations.

System

A system is a collection of interconnected components or elements that work together to perform a specific function or achieve a particular objective.

Time

Time refers to a measurable dimension in which events occur sequentially and can be used to qualify the duration between occurences.

Wired Communication

Wired communication refers to the transmission of data or signals through physical connections such as cables or wires.

  • Software
  • Software System
  • System Documentation

Description

Cloud refers to a network of remote servers that store, manage, and process data and applications, providing on-demand access and scalable computing resources over the internet. The Cloud lobe of the Digital Reference ontology models AH Local Cloud, Communication Technology, Data Format and Model, Device, and Documentation Document. It also maps the topics of Information Model, Local Network, Method, SoA Property, Software and Software System, system Documentation and System of Systems. It represents the notion of Service, Service Documentation, Service-Oriented Architecture and Architecture Protocols.

Service

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Service
Description

In the context of the Arrowhead Framework a Service is the information exchanged from a providing system to a consuming system. • is based on a number of service orientation principles derived from high level objectives and properties of the Arrowhead framework • can be realized by an arbitrary number of service producers and service consumers • a system can consume a number of services, process and provide other services to fulfil a more complex task • can only be provided by technical systems • can support operational activities within business processes • can support non-functional requirements, such as real-time • can have stakeholders, with an interest in business benefit, in one or more specific area of interest • can have an appointed stakeholder, responsible for the governance of the Service (definition, development). (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4 & Arrowhead Device Registry Presentation)

has sub-classes: AH Service

is disjoint with: Software System

has object properties: has data model , has information model , has method , is service documented by , produced by , uses comm tech , uses communication security mechanism , uses data format , uses transfer protocol , defines compliant service , is data model of , is information model of , is method of , is service producer of , produces

Decision Maker Type

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Planning#Decision_Maker_Type
Description

We distinguish human decision-makers (human DECISION-MAKING UNITS) from fully automated DECISION-MAKING UNITS where computers make fully automated decisions. Between these two extremes there are semi-automated decisions, where a computer provides several decision alternatives and a human decision-maker chooses among them. Note that the decision-maker type can change over time.

has sub-classes: Semi Automated , automated , human

has object properties: has decision maker type

back to Planning Lobe

Planning Constraint

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Planning#Planning_Constraint
Description

A PLANNING CONSTRAINT restricts the action space. This space is formed by alternative actions that are a result of the planning decisions (Schneeweis 2003). In the planning domain, PLANNING CONSTRAINTS, often the capacity offered by resources, limit the quantities that are assigned to the PLANNING OBJECTS or impact the temporal properties of PLANNING OBJECTS.

has sub-classes: Resource Availability Constraints , Resource Compatibility Constraints , temporal constraints

Power Lobe

IRI
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr#Power_Lobe
Super Class Of
  • Control Method
  • Device Configuration
  • Device Element
  • Document

  • Gate Driver

  • Information Object
  • Operation Mode
  • Process
  • Process Input
  • Process Output
  • Product
  • Resistance
  • SiC MOSFET
  • Switcher
  • Voltage
Description

Power refers to the electrical energy consumed or dissipated by electronic devices or components during their operation, and is a crucial consideration for efficiency and performance optimization. The Power lobe models the Amplication Switching Device, Control Method, Device Configuration and Element, Document, Entity, and Gate Driver. It also represents the notions of Industrial Sector, Information Object, Operation Mode, Process, Process Input and Output. It maps the topics of Product, Resistance, SiC MOSFET, switcher, and Voltage.

Industrial Sector

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-PWR#Industrial_Sector
Description

The collection of all localized groups of enterprises that are producers of industrial commodities, in which each such group together forms the major industrial sector for the region. 'Industrial commodities' includes MechanicalDevices and basic industrial materials. Examples include 'the world industrial sector', the 'industrial sector of China'. The Chinese water pump industry would not be an exemplar of IndustrialEconomicSector but would rather be a sub-industry (see subIndustries) of it. On the other hand, chinese water pump manufacturers would be considered groupMembers of 'the industrial sector of China'. This classification is done by The Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) is an industry taxonomy developed in 1999 by MSCI and Standard & Poor's (S&P) for use by the global financial community. The GICS structure consists of 11 sectors, 24 industry groups, 68 industries and 157 sub-industries[1] into which S&P has categorized all major public companies

Is defined by:

has sub-classes: Communication Services , Consumer Discretionary , Consumer Staples , Energy , Financial , Healthcare , Industrials , Information Technology , Materials , Real Estate , Utilities

back to Power Lobe

Description

The superclass of all classes describing products or services types, either by nature or purpose. Examples for such subclasses are "TV set", "vacuum cleaner", etc. An instance of this class can be either an actual product or service (gr:Individual), a placeholder instance for unknown instances of a mass-produced commodity (gr:SomeItems), or a model / prototype specification (gr:ProductOrServiceModel). When in doubt, use gr:SomeItems. Examples: a) MyCellphone123, i.e. my personal, tangible cell phone (gr:Individual) b) Siemens1234, i.e. the Siemens cell phone make and model 1234 (gr:ProductOrServiceModel) c) dummyCellPhone123 as a placeholder for actual instances of a certain kind of cell phones (gr:SomeItems)

Integration Level

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-OOSMP#Integration_Level
Description

Each motor control and drive solution has an integration level which states if the different stage are built in an integrated or discrete way. The stages of a motor control and drive solution are "Controller", "Driver", "Power Stage". Following this, the different integration levels are "discrete" (not integrated), "fully integrated", "integrated controller driver", "integrated driver power stage", "integrated power stage".

is equivalent to: discrete solution integration level , fully integrated solution integration level , integrated controller driver solution integration level , integrated driver power stage solution integration level , integrated power stage solution integration level

has object properties: is integration level of , has integration level

product

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-DF#Product
Description

A product is a good that fulfills a prescribed set of requirements (for instance, form, fit, and function). A set of alternative BOMs might be associated with each product. The manufacturing process is complicated by binning and substitution (in production). Binning refers to the process that an item can become one of several products based on tested levels of performance, for instance, speed.

is equivalent to: Product

Mask

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-SO#Mask
Description

A transparent (glass or quartz) plate covered with an array of patterns used in making an IC. Each pattern consists of opaque and transparent areas that define the size and shape of all circuit and device elements. The mask is used to expose selected areas, and defines the areas to be processed. Masks may use emulsion, chrome, iron oxide, silicon or other material to produce the opaque areas.

has object properties: requires

Every product uses a specific route in its value stream, i.e. the complete sequence of operations with all mandatory and optional operations necessary to complete the product. A route makes use of the single operations. (workflow descriptive master entity)

Sensor Lobe

IRI
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr#Sensor_Lobe
Super Class Of
  • Mounting Style
  • Sensing Type
  • actuation
  • deployment
  • observation
  • observation collection
  • platform
  • procedure
  • property
  • relationship nature
  • result
  • sample relationship
  • sampling
Description

A sensor is a device or component that detects and measures physical, chemical or environmental parameters and converts them into electrical signals for futher analysis or use. The Sensor lobes models the notion of a System and its Deployment. It maps the topics of Actuation, Feature of Interest, Input, Mounting Style, Observation and Observation Collection, and Output. It also represents Platform, Procedure, Property, Relationship Nature, Result, Sample Relationship, Sampling, Sensing Type, and Stimulus.

Fieldbus Communication Profile Family

IRI http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AT#Fieldbus_Communication_Profile_Family
Description

A field bus is a bus system that connects field devices such as sensors and actuators in a plant for the purpose of communication with an automation device. If several communication participants send their messages over the same line, then it must be specified who (identifier) says what (measured value, command) and when (initiative). There are standardized protocols for this. The first generation of fieldbus technology was developed in the 1980s to replace the parallel wiring of binary signals and analog signal transmission that had been common until then with digital transmission technology. Today, many different fieldbus systems with different characteristics are established on the market. Since 1999, fieldbuses have been standardized worldwide in the IEC 61158 standard (Digital data communication for measurement and control - Fieldbus for use in industrial control systems) and by the IEC 61784 standard. The second generation of fieldbus technology is based on real-time Ethernet (Industrial Ethernet). A fieldbus defines a complete protocol stack over the 7 layers of the OSI layer model. If necessary, not all layers are occupied. Example for first generation fieldbus is Profibus, Example for second generation fieldbus is ProfiNet.

has sub-classes: CPF1 FOUNDATION Fieldbus , CPF10 VNET IP , CPF11 TC Net , CPF12 Ether CAT , CPF13 Ethernet Powerlink , CPF14 EPA , CPF15 Mod Bus , CPF16 SERCOS , CPF17 RAPI Net , CPF18 Safety Net P , CPF2 Control Net , CPF3 Profibus Profi Net , CPF4 P NET , CPF5 World FIP , CPF6 INTERBUS , CPF7 Swift Net , CPF8 CC Link , CPF9 HART

back to Wired Communication Lobe

has sub-classes: ISA-95 Comm 1 1 , ISA-95 Comm 1 2 , ISA-95 Comm 2 2 , ISA-95 Comm 2 3 , ISA-95 Comm 3 3 , ISA-95 Comm 3 4 , ISA-95 Comm 4 4

documents AH service method

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#documents_AH_service_method
has super-properties
documents service part
has domain
Interface Design Description IDD
has range
Method
Relation between an Interface Design Description document (of a specific service) and a method of this service. The relation expresses that the IDD document documents the methods of the service the IDD belongs to. With this, a consistency check would be possible: IF a service S has a method M AND the IDD IDD_S is part of the service documentation of S (i.e. IDD_S is the IDD of S) THEN IDD_S should contain a documentation of M.

has criterias

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Planning#has_criterias
has domain
Planing Purpose
has range
criteria
A criterion is assigned to each performance measure that belongs to a PLANNING PURPOSE. Typical criteria are maximization, minimization, i.e. if an optimization problem is considered, or larger or smaller than a prescribed value of the certain performance measure, a so-called target, i.e. if a satisfaction problem is solved. In a multi-criteria setting, the dominance concept for plans is of interest.

refers to

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refers_to
has sub-properties
refers to CP , refers to IDD , refers to SD , refers to SP , refers to So SD , refers to Sy SD , refers to Sy SDD
has domain
Documentation Document
has range
Documentation Document
is inverse of
is referred to by
describes the relation between two documentation documents that one document refers to another document. To our best knowledge, the following relations hold between different types of documentation documents: - an IDD refers to exactly one SD. - an SD is referred to by one or more IDD (each stating a way of implementing the service with a specific technolopgy (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4)) - an IDD refers to at most one CP (if it not refers to a CP, then the IDD contains all CP information by itself) - an IDD refers to n SP, 0 <= n (if it not refers to a SP, then the IDD contains all SP information by itself) - a SySD refers to one or more IDDs (that is, a system produces one or more services). - a SySDD refers to one or more SySD's. (Remark HB: I don't understand this. How can one concrete white box description of a system fulfill (support / implement) different black box descriptions of systems? The other way around seems to be possible as between SDs and IDDs). - an SoSD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SoSD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySDDs.

refers to

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Incoterms#refers_to
has domain
transfer action
has range
product

refers to CP

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refers_to_CP
has super-properties
refers to
has domain
Interface Design Description IDD
has range
Communication Profile
an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Communication Profile (CP). No other documentation document can refer to a CP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a CP, but this is not mandatory. CPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same CP. Then the CP information should be extracted to an CP document and the IDDs of all services that use this CP shall refer to this CP. If the CP is unique for a specific service, the CP information can directly be included in the IDD. If the IDD refers to a CP, this must be a unique reference. That is, one IDD must not refer to different CPs. Hence this object property is functional. (If the service could be implemented using different communication technologies, each implementation would need an own IDD!!).

refers to SP

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refers_to_SP
has super-properties
refers to
has domain
Interface Design Description IDD
has range
Semantic Profile
an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Semantic Profile (SP). No other documentation document can refer to a SP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a SP, but this is not mandatory. SPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same SP. Then the SCP information should be extracted to an SP document and the IDDs of all services that use this SP shall refer to this SP. If the SP is unique for a specific service, the SP information can directly be included in the IDD. References to SPs are not necessarily unique for an IDD. That is, different methods of the service documented by the IDD can use different Semantic Profiles.

decision rights

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Planning#decision_rights
has super-properties
top data property
has domain
Decision Making Unit
has range
string
This property will allow a DECISION-MAKING UNIT to negotiate the instruction provided by other DECISION-MAKING UNIT. In a conventional or strict hierarchical setting, negotiations of instruction provided by superior DECISION-MAKING UNITs are impossible. In a distributed hierarchical setting in the sense of Schneeweiss (2003) reactions of the DECISION-MAKING UNIT which can lead to negotiations are possible (Schneeweiss 2003).

level

IRI:
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-Planning#level
has super-properties
top data property
has domain
edge
Planning Situation
has range
string
Each vertex has a level. The highest level is assigned to vertices that do not receive instructions from other vertices. The vertices belonging to the second highest level receive instructions only from vertices of the highest level. This definition can be repeated in a recursive manner. Reactions are only possible from vertices of level k-1 to vertices of level k or level k-1.
